<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:202px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Amen_break_sample_image.png" class="image" title="Part of the waveform for the Amen break including the crash at the end."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Amen_break_sample_image.png/200px-Amen_break_sample_image.png" width="200" height="148" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Amen_break_sample_image.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Part of the waveform for the Amen break including the crash at the end.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The <b>"Amen break"</b> (usually pronounced <span title="Pronunciation in the International Phonetic Alphabet (IPA)" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_English" title="Wikipedia:IPA for English">/ɑːˈmɛn/</a></span><sup class="noprint Template-Fact"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources&#160;since May 2008" style="white-space: nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</span></sup>) was a drum solo performed by <a href="/wiki/Gregory_Cylvester_Coleman" title="Gregory Cylvester Coleman" class="mw-redirect">Gregory Sylvester "G.C." Coleman</a>.</p>
<p>The "Amen Break", "Amen", or imitations thereof, are frequently used as <a href="/wiki/Sampling_(music)" title="Sampling (music)">sampled</a> <a href="/wiki/Drum" title="Drum">drum</a> <a href="/wiki/Music_loop" title="Music loop">loops</a> in <a href="/wiki/Hip_hop_music" title="Hip hop music">hip hop</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jungle_(music)" title="Jungle (music)" class="mw-redirect">jungle</a>, <a href="/wiki/Breakcore" title="Breakcore">breakcore</a> and <a href="/wiki/Drum_and_bass" title="Drum and bass">drum and bass</a> music. It is 5.20 seconds long and consists of 4 bars of the drum-solo sampled from the song "Amen, Brother" as performed by the 1960s <a href="/wiki/Funk" title="Funk">funk</a> and <a href="/wiki/Soul_music" title="Soul music">soul</a> outfit <a href="/wiki/The_Winstons" title="The Winstons">The Winstons</a>. The song is an up-tempo instrumental rendition of an older <a href="/wiki/Gospel_music" title="Gospel music">gospel music</a> classic. The Winstons' version was released as a B-side of the <a href="/wiki/Extended_play" title="Extended play">45</a> <a href="/wiki/Revolutions_per_minute" title="Revolutions per minute">RPM</a> <a href="/wiki/Single_(music)" title="Single (music)">7-inch</a> vinyl single "<a href="/wiki/Color_Him_Father" title="Color Him Father">Color Him Father</a>" in 1969 on Metromedia (MMS-117), and is currently available on several compilations and on a <a href="/wiki/12-inch_single" title="12-inch single">12-inch</a> vinyl re-release together with other songs by <a href="/wiki/The_Winstons" title="The Winstons">The Winstons</a>.</p>
<p>The Amen Break was used extensively in early hiphop and sample-based music, and became the basis for drum-and-bass and jungle music--"a six-second clip that spawned several entire subcultures" <sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
